## Tech Stack

- **Framework**: Next.js (App Router)
- **UI**: React + TypeScript
- **Backend**: AWS Lambda (Node.js) + API Gateway
- **Database**: DynamoDB
- **Infrastructure**: Terraform
- **CI/CD**: GitHub Actions
- **Hosting**: CloudFront + S3

## Project Structure

```
src/          # Next.js app source (App Router)
  app/        # Routes and layouts
  components/ # Shared React components
lambda/       # AWS Lambda function handlers
terraform/    # Infrastructure as code
.github/
  workflows/  # GitHub Actions CI/CD pipelines
```

## Development

Always use the public npm registry explicitly:

```bash
npm install --registry=https://registry.npmjs.org/
npm run dev       # Start Next.js dev server (http://localhost:3000)
npm run build     # Production build
npm run typecheck # Run TypeScript type checking
npm run lint      # Run ESLint
```

When installing new packages, always specify the public registry:

```bash
npm install <package> --registry=https://registry.npmjs.org/
```

## Key Conventions

- All components are TypeScript (`.tsx`)
- Use the App Router (`src/app/`) — no Pages Router
- Lambda handlers live in `lambda/` and are deployed independently via Terraform
- Infrastructure changes require a PR — the `deploy.yaml` workflow applies Terraform on merge to `main`

